{{Infobox NRHP | name = Edward Douglass White House | nrhp_type = nhl | image = EDWhite.jpg | caption = | location = 2295 [[Louisiana Highway 1|LA 1]], [[Thibodaux, Louisiana]] | coordinates = {{coord|29.8242|-90.91152|format=dms|display=inline,title,source:ProprioMeOW}} | locmapin = Louisiana#USA | area = {{convert|3|acre|ha}} | built = 1790 | architect = | architecture = | designated_nrhp_type = December 8, 1976<ref name="nhlsum">{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1625&ResourceType=Building|title=Edward Douglass White House|accessdate=2008-01-31|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref> | added = December 8, 1976 | refnum = 76000964<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2013a}}</ref> }}
The '''Edward Douglass White House''', also known as '''Edward Douglass White Louisiana State Commemorative Area''', is a state historic site near [[Thibodaux, Louisiana]]. The house was home to both [[Edward Douglass White, Sr.]], the tenth governor of the state of Louisiana, and his son, [[Edward Douglass White]], a U.S. senator and a [[Chief Justice of the United States]]. It was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1976 for its association with the latter White, whose influential decision in ''[[Standard Oil Co. of New Jersey v. United States]]'', while resulting in the breakup of [[Standard Oil]], weakened the [[Sherman Antitrust Act]] by its adoption of the [[rule of reason]].<ref name="nrhpinv2"/>
==History== The house was built from hand-hewn cypress as a [[Creole cottage|Creole-style raised cottage]]. The house was built on the banks of [[Bayou Lafourche]] facing what is now [[Louisiana Highway 1]]. E.D. White, Sr. purchased the property in 1829 from Guillaume Arcement, and around 1834 began remodeling the house to reflect the prevalent [[Greek revival architecture|Greek revival]] style of architecture.<ref name="lsm">{{cite web |title=E.D. White Historic Site - Louisiana State Museum |url=http://louisianastatemuseum.org/museums/ed-white-historic-site/ |accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref> It was declared a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1976.<ref name="nhlsum"/><ref name="nrhpinv2">{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Edward Douglass White House / Edward Douglass White Louisiana State Commemorative Area|url={{NHLS url|id=76000964}} |format=pdf|date=April 1976 |author=George R. Adams and Ralph Christian |publisher=National Park Service}} and {{NHLS url|id=76000964|title=''Accompanying 2 photos, exterior, from 1976.''|photos=y}}&nbsp;{{small|(999&nbsp;KB)}}</ref>
==Architecture== The main floor includes a central hallway dividing four rooms, reflecting the typical symmetry of Greek Revival architecture. An inverted stairwell at the end of the hall leads to two bedrooms on the second floor. The high ceilings, wide front gallery, and raised brick cellar served to cool the house during the summer.<ref name="lsm"/>
==Museum== The house is owned by the [[Louisiana State Museum]] and is operated as a [[historic house museum]] known as the '''E. D. White Historic Site'''. An exhibit inside the home demonstrates the history of the Bayou Lafourche area, with features on the [[Chitimacha|Chitimacha Indians]], [[Acadiens|Acadian settlers]], slavery, sugar cane plantations, and the White family.<ref name="lsm"/>
==See also== *[[List of National Historic Landmarks in Louisiana]] *[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Lafourche Parish, Louisiana]]
