{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = National Archival Services of Norway |nativename = Arkivverket |nativename_a = |nativename_r = |logo = Coat of arms of Norway.svg |logo_width = 100px |logo_caption = |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |picture = Norways national archive.jpg |picture_width = 300px |picture_caption = |formed = 1817 |headquarters = [[Oslo]] |coordinates = |employees = 190 |budget = |minister1_name = |minister1_pfo = |minister2_name = |minister2_pfo = |chief1_name = |chief1_position = |chief2_name = |chief2_position = |agency_type = |parent_agency = |child1_agency = |child2_agency = |website = [http://www.arkivverket.no www.arkivverket.no] |footnotes = |map = |map_width = |map_caption = }}
The '''National Archival Services of Norway''' ({{lang-no|Arkivverket}}) is a [[Norwegian government agencies|Norwegian government agency]] that is responsible for keeping state [[archive]]s, conducts control of public archiving and works to preserve private archives. It is subordinate to the [[Norwegian Ministry of Culture and Church Affairs|Ministry of Culture and Church Affairs]] and consists of the [[National Archives of Norway|National Archive]] ({{lang|no|Riksarkivet}}), eight regional state archives ({{lang|no|statsarkiv}}) and [[The Sámi Archives]] ({{lang|no|Samisk arkiv}}). The organization has 190 employees and about {{convert|120|km|sp=us}} of materials. The oldest complete document is from 1189.<ref name=about>{{cite web |url=http://www.arkivverket.no/english/about.html |title=The National Archival Services of Norway |publisher=National Archival Services of Norway |accessdate=25 November 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100209090555/http://www.arkivverket.no/english/about.html |archivedate=9 February 2010 |df= }}</ref> It is a letter (a so-called diploma) issued on 28 January 1189 by [[Pope Clement III]] (1187-1191) to all clergymen in Norway.<ref>[http://www.arkivverket.no/english/samples/treasures.html Treasures. From the National Archives Services of Norway website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502012431/http://www.arkivverket.no/english/samples/treasures.html |date=2009-05-02 }}. Retrieved 1 December 2009.</ref>
The National Archive is located at [[Sognsvann]] in Oslo and preserves all central government papers from when they become 25 years old, as well as some archives from private individuals, companies and organizations. The National Archive is also responsible for control. The state archives are responsible for local and regional government and state agencies, as well as archives from private people, companies, institutions and organizations. The local archives are located in [[Regional State Archives in Bergen|Bergen]], [[Regional State Archives in Hamar|Hamar]], [[Regional State Archives in Kongsberg|Kongsberg]], [[Regional State Archives in Kristiansand|Kristiansand]], [[Regional State Archives in Oslo|Oslo]], [[Regional State Archives in Stavanger|Stavanger]], [[Regional State Archives in Tromsø|Tromsø]] and [[Regional State Archives in Trondheim|Trondheim]].<ref name=about />
The Digital Archive is a web site that publishes selected works. This includes census data from 1801, 1865, 1875, 1900 and 1910, a database of emigrants and scanned church, probate and court records.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://digitalarkivet.uib.no/cgi-win/WebFront.exe?slag=vis&tekst=meldingar&spraak=e |title=English |publisher=National Archival Services of Norway |accessdate=25 November 2009}}</ref> The agency publishes three magazines: '' Arkivmagasinet'', ''Nytt fra Statsarkivet i Oslo'' and ''Bergensposten''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkivverket.no/arkivverket/publikasjoner.html |title=Publikasjoner |publisher=National Archival Services of Norway |accessdate=25 November 2009 |language=Norwegian |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207140252/http://arkivverket.no/arkivverket/publikasjoner.html |archivedate=February 7, 2009 }}</ref> The agency is regulated by the ''Archive Act'' of 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkivverket.no/arkivverket/lover/arkivloven.html |title=Arkivloven |publisher=National Archival Services of Norway |accessdate=25 November 2009 |language=Norwegian |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514082313/http://www.arkivverket.no/arkivverket/lover/arkivloven.html |archivedate=May 14, 2009 }}</ref> The archives are open to anyone, but there are restrictions on certain types of documents that may contain sensitive or personal information, or could pose a threat to national security. These documents are released to the public between 60 and 100 years after the date of publishing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkivverket.no/arkivverket/bruk.html |title=Bruk |publisher=National Archival Services of Norway |accessdate=25 November 2009 |language=Norwegian |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212101813/http://www.arkivverket.no/arkivverket/bruk.html |archivedate=February 12, 2010 }}</ref>
== See also == * [[List of national archives]]
