{{Chinese |pic=TempleofHeaven-HallofPrayer.jpg |piccap=[[Temple of Heaven]], an AAAAA-rated tourist attraction in [[Beijing]] |order=st |s={{linktext|旅游|景区|质量|等级}} |t=旅遊景區質量等級 |p=Lǚyóu Jǐngqū Zhìliàng Děngjí |l=Tourist Scenic Area Quality Ranking }} '''Tourist Attraction Rating Categories of China''' ({{zh|旅游景区质量等级}}) is a rating system used by the Chinese authorities to determine the quality of the attraction relative to its peers in terms of safety, cleanliness, sanitation and transportation. It is broken up into five categories which are''' '''A (or 1A, the lowest level), AA (2A), AAA (3A), AAAA (4A) and AAAAA (5A, the highest level).
== Ratings == {| class="wikitable sortable" !Ratings !alternate !Level |- |A |1A |lowest |- |AA |2A | |- |AAA |3A | |- |AAAA |4A | |- |[[Chinese AAAAA-rated tourist attractions|AAAAA]] |5A |highest |}
== Assessment == The categories are awarded based on, amongst other factors, the importance of the site, transportation, tours as well as issues related to safety, cleanliness and sanitation. The system was established in 1999 and extended in 2004 (when the category AAAAA was introduced). The ratings are administered by the [[China National Tourism Administration]]{{needs update|date=April 2018}} (CNTA) and are based on the code "Categories and Rating Standard of Tourist Attractions".<ref>{{cite book|title=Tourism in China: Destination, Cultures and Communities|editor=Chris Ryan and Gu Huimin|author=Chris Ryan, Gu Huimin and Fang Meng|edition=1|year=2009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GH0790IPIE8C&printsec=frontcover|isbn=9780203886366|chapter=Destination planning in China|pages=11–37}}</ref>
